<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-720-346  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 720 346.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  August 10 1990 n1488* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Now Philips' Laser Magnetic has write-once+erasable drive. (LaserMagnetic Storage International Co.) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Laser Magnetic Storage International Co. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Laser Magnetic Storage LaserDrive 520 (Optical disk drive)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionErasable Optical MemoryOptical DisksDisk Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NOW PHILIPS' LASER MAGNETIC HAS WRITE-ONCE+ERASABLE DRIVEandM;Colorado Springs-based Laser Magnetic Storage International Co is catching upwith Pioneer Corp's Pioneer Communications of America, headquartered in UpperSaddle River, New Jersey, in terms of optical disk drive product.andP;  LastOctober, the Japanese company revealed its DE-U500 disk subsystem designed tobe used with write-once and erasable 5.25&quot; optical disks (CI No 1,289), andthese are now being distributed in the UK by HTEC Ltd of Southampton (CI No1,339).andP;  Now Laser Magnetic Storage also has a dual-function drive subsystemof its own, called the LaserDrive 520.andP;  Its drive has very similarspecifications to the Pioneer unit which will sell in September at an OEMprice of $2,395.andP;  End-user prices will be approximately double this.andP;  LaserMagnetic was a joint venture set up by Philips NV and Control Data Corp in1979 to develop optical media and disk drives, but is now coming under thecomplete control of Philips (CI No 1,384).andP;  The LD 520 will be able to readdisks written by existing LD 510 write-once drives and can use LM 510write-once cartridges that cost $113 as well as rewritable optical disks thatcost $200.andO;</TEXT></DOC>